# DevOps Rules, Skills & Workflows — Walkthrough

All **12 files** created under `.windsurf/` in 3 folders.

---

## Final Structure

```
.windsurf/
├── rules/
│   ├── devops-security.md      # Container hardening, secrets, RBAC, network policies, supply-chain
│   ├── blast-radius.md         # Namespace isolation, PDB, rollback, progressive delivery, graceful shutdown
│   └── code-quality.md         # Dockerfile lint, Helm lint, YAML validation, Node/Spring quality, Git hygiene
├── skills/
│   ├── github-actions/SKILL.md    # CI/CD templates (Node + Spring Boot), reusable workflows, OIDC, matrix, composites
│   ├── kubernetes-helm/SKILL.md   # Full chart structure, deployment/network-policy/helpers templates, commands cheat sheet
│   ├── trivy-sonarqube/SKILL.md   # Image/FS/IaC scanning, quality gates, SonarQube for Node + Spring, combined CI job
│   └── nodejs-springboot/SKILL.md # Production Dockerfiles, health endpoints, graceful shutdown, 12-factor compliance
└── workflows/
    ├── ci-pipeline.md          # Build → test → scan → publish (step-by-step)
    ├── cd-deploy.md            # Staging → prod promotion via Helm, OIDC, rollback, canary
    ├── security-scan.md        # Local + CI Trivy & SonarQube scanning runbook
    ├── incident-response.md    # Detect → rollback → diagnose → communicate → fix → post-mortem
    └── helm-chart-create.md    # Scaffold → configure → validate → package → publish
```

## Key Design Decisions

| Concern | Approach |
|---------|----------|
| **Security** | Default-deny network policies, non-root containers, OIDC auth, pinned action SHAs, Trivy + SonarQube gates |
| **Blast Radius** | Namespace isolation, PDB, atomic Helm deploys, progressive delivery, graceful shutdown |
| **Simplicity** | Copy-paste ready templates, values-per-env pattern, reusable workflows, cheat sheets |

## How Windsurf Uses These

- **Rules** → always-on guardrails (AI reads them on every prompt)
- **Skills** → on-demand reference (AI reads when the task matches the skill)
- **Workflows** → slash-command runbooks (invoked via `/ci-pipeline`, `/cd-deploy`, etc.)
